poem:
The Pierrafallune

The chiselclocks were ticking teak in tessellated shade,  
When mulbervyne and lepordile along the lintels played;  
"O warn the cutters!" caromed crows, "Beware the Mozaicfright—  
For shards will stitch your sight to stone in pietra dura night!"  

He polished up his onyx helm, he whetted carbon plume;  
He lashed a carbuncleum clasp about his drohlmar loom;  
With prism’d grout and riptmin tools he wove a fluorite sheen—  
Then sought where moon-mozaics slept in cinch-embedded scene.  

The quarry leered with jazelglass; green breccias softly groaned;  
Where scaglit wings and crystal sings through grommet-cold intoned.  
Then flambjara!—adrift, adazzle—the Chromalume unfurled,  
Its tessellurking marmatoid eyes mailshard’d at the world.  

"One blow, cobaltian blade, one truth-cut in the seam!"  
He struck between the eye of jade and turquoise-breasted dream;  
Slate skirr!—the fracture, sunlit, shrilled; the glamour hiss’d away;  
A thousand prismed splinters stilled. Dawn drank the jagged day.  

"Has thou flayed the Mozaicfright? Good chislor, twist and twine!"  
Inlaid applause flashed sapphire, sang out the quarry-line;  
He bore the reglow-shivered core where first the warning fell,  
And, chink by chink, the shattered skies reseeded skies as well.  

The chiselclocks resumed their tick in tessellated day,  
The mulbervyne and lepordile along the lintels play;  
"O heed the cutters!" carom crows—yet mirthful now they cry—  
"For sun-split stone now safely shines in pietra dura sky!"

Fiddle Rosinwhirl  

’Twas plick and murk inside the pract’ry, fret-slats glaring gluff,  
When brinish gwoom from gut-strung gloam sang scraddled, skin-tight stuff;  
Beware, the Rosinwhirl, my boy, its crumbéd atoms puff—  
It whips to whispers gritty frost, a resin diamond-crust’d bluff.  

He whetted bow with hushled silt, tapped knuckles, flexed aplomb;  
His elbow angled krinkle-tight, he damped the ticking thomb;  
He slung the rosiny hood and pack, a pouch of brittle bomb;  
He whistled thrice a burl-grain tune—counterclockwise, glumm.  

Vorp-bow athrum, he tiptocked through the bowsprung brattle hall;  
A harrumph of hogo smouldered where pegs leaned like a wall;  
He snortled low— *ploof!* —and caught the drifting rosin-squall;  
It skreled like gravel muskets banged, a waxéd, grey-black squall.  

**Cre-e-e-eak! Thring-gg!** The Rosinwhirl unrawwred, clabber-coil—  
A whorl of dead-horse dandruff flaring, chalked on trembling soil;  
Its grit-eyes flicked ssshick-schlick glass, its hiss a bubble-boil;  
He step-swung hot, sawed half-full *down-*slash—snap bowstringed broil!  

Snicker-snack broke bow-snap, sword-thin flat of amber light;  
The dusty beast exploded— *paf!* —one vast candescent white;  
He stood astoned, wrist mantled 'rose, in soundless starry night;  
He picked the shard, the huskéd note, a brittle crumb—delight.  

He wheeled, his pocket plink-plank plumped with triumph toasted new;  
A laugh-a-swish swam through the coom, the brattle hall clean-blue;  
The curtain shut—climactic hush—and cello-thunder true—  
’Twas plick and murk inside the pract’ry, fret-slats glaring gluff anew
